would make the game a
lot more cool or awesome,

00:11:19.940 --> 00:11:23.120
but are hard to prioritize
and just way too much

00:11:23.120 --> 00:11:25.060
to stack on top of the game.

00:11:25.060 --> 00:11:26.800
So that was the downside.

00:11:26.800 --> 00:11:32.210
And it was just hard to
control-- it was hard to scope

00:11:32.210 --> 00:11:34.720
the game down to the five
minutes game we needed

00:11:34.720 --> 00:11:37.710
to create for the project.

00:11:37.710 --> 00:11:41.560
Gitter was good with
the [INAUDIBLE].

00:11:41.560 --> 00:11:44.540
If everybody was on and
everybody used it all the time,

00:11:44.540 --> 00:11:45.810
it would be ideal.

00:11:45.810 --> 00:11:49.620
But since a lot of us are on the
go and working on other things,

00:11:49.620 --> 00:11:54.620
in classes while people are
working, using something else

00:11:54.620 --> 00:11:57.560
might have been better, like
g-chat or Facebook, something

00:11:57.560 --> 00:11:59.140
you can access
from a smartphone,

00:11:59.140 --> 00:12:02.890
or something more instantaneous.

00:12:02.890 --> 00:12:05.887
We would just get-- if you
weren't on Gitter at the time,

00:12:05.887 --> 00:12:07.720
it would send you a
notification being like,

00:12:07.720 --> 00:12:09.350
you missed these messages.

00:12:09.350 --> 00:12:13.240
Which is almost as delayed
a message as email.

00:12:13.240 --> 00:12:15.804
So it was kind of pointless
other than the fact

00:12:15.804 --> 00:12:17.220
that it was
integrated with GitHub

00:12:17.220 --> 00:12:20.986
and you could see who was
online at the same time as you.

00:12:20.986 --> 00:12:22.360
Another thing that
didn't work is

00:12:22.360 --> 00:12:24.560
that meetings are really,
really hard to coordinate

00:12:24.560 --> 00:12:26.290
with seven people.

00:12:26.290 --> 00:12:32.880
And what ended up happening
was that we would all be like,

00:12:32.880 --> 00:12:36.330
OK, so half of us are
free this day, six of us

00:12:36.330 --> 00:12:38.350
are free this other time.

00:12:38.350 --> 00:12:39.560
Let's meet then.

00:12:39.560 --> 00:12:41.390
And then we wouldn't
decide a specific time

00:12:41.390 --> 00:12:43.440
within the time
were free to meet.

00:12:43.440 --> 00:12:46.730
And then by the time we noticed
this, ti would like that day.

00:12:46.730 --> 00:12:49.500
And it was just hard to
coordinate everything

00:12:49.500 --> 00:12:52.630
after it got to that point.

00:12:52.630 --> 00:12:57.230
So for the future,
I believe we would

00:12:57.230 --> 00:12:59.850
have to have a fully
dedicated scrum master.

00:12:59.850 --> 00:13:02.600
And I really mean
fully dedicated,

00:13:02.600 --> 00:13:05.750
not scrum master AKA
programmer on the side,

00:13:05.750 --> 00:13:08.917
or scrum master who also gets
music done and play tests,

00:13:08.917 --> 00:13:10.000
well it does play testing.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:13.660
Everybody play tests, but a
fully dedicated scrum master

00:13:13.660 --> 00:13:16.000
to make sure that
everybody's on tasks,

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:17.990
that the meetings
will get scheduled,

00:13:17.990 --> 00:13:20.990
and that the tasks
are prioritized.

00:13:20.990 --> 00:13:24.590
And if something falls through,
they're the person to talk to,

00:13:24.590 --> 00:13:27.100
they're the person who's going
to make you stop freaking out

00:13:27.100 --> 00:13:29.380
that this task took
like three times as long

00:13:29.380 --> 00:13:32.060
as you've estimated it for.

00:13:32.060 --> 00:13:34.710
We didn't have this one
person dedicated to that.

00:13:34.710 --> 00:13:38.600
Everybody was like a jack
of all trades in our group.

00:13:38.600 --> 00:13:41.930
So not having that
one person to talk to,

00:13:41.930 --> 00:13:47.360
go to, made task
prioritization really fuzzy,

00:13:47.360 --> 00:13:50.880
and made everything kind of
come together really late.

00:13:50.880 --> 00:13:53.294
And it was hard to
hold people accountable

00:13:53.294 --> 00:13:54.960
because there wasn't
that one person who

00:13:54.960 --> 00:13:57.346
was on top of everybody.

00:13:57.346 --> 00:13:59.750
Another thing we
had to do earlier

00:13:59.750 --> 00:14:00.940
would be feature cutting.

00:14:00.940 --> 00:14:04.680
Because if you don't cut
features definitively earlier,

00:14:04.680 --> 00:14:07.770
you'll still have it lingering
on some people's minds.

00:14:07.770 --> 00:14:09.770
Oh, I have to do this
so that in the future

00:14:09.770 --> 00:14:12.860
we're going to maybe
use this feature.

00:14:12.860 --> 00:14:14.760
But if you cut these
features early,

00:14:14.760 --> 00:14:20.370
you limit the propensity to
have bugs, or stuff like that.

00:14:20.370 --> 00:14:23.750
While it's unfortunate that
you have to cut features,

00:14:23.750 --> 00:14:25.270
it's necessary.

00:14:25.270 --> 00:14:29.320
So doing it earlier is
the best time to do it.

00:14:29.320 --> 00:14:31.200
Another thing is,
like I said before,

00:14:31.200 --> 00:14:32.710
a native messaging system.

00:14:32.710 --> 00:14:37.680
Gitter was cute but didn't
actually work in the way

00:14:37.680 --> 00:14:38.990
that we wanted it to work.

00:14:38.990 --> 00:14:41.840
It wasn't instantaneous
between all members.

00:14:41.840 --> 00:14:45.570
It's hard to find a messaging
system that everybody likes.

00:14:45.570 --> 00:14:50.140
But I think something like
G-chat or Facebook messaging,

00:14:50.140 --> 00:14:52.310
something instantaneous
like that that most people

00:14:52.310 --> 00:14:57.157
use already should
be used as a group

00:14:57.157 --> 00:14:58.865
so that everybody can
be on the same page

00:14:58.865 --> 00:15:03.860
and have access to
the instant messaging.

00:15:03.860 --> 00:15:07.490
Yeah, our game is there
if you want to play it.

