00:17:51.640 --> 00:17:56.550
OK with losing all their
money in one turn [INAUDIBLE].

00:17:56.550 --> 00:18:01.620
Because, hey, the
description of it was funny.

00:18:01.620 --> 00:18:06.140
And so the third thing that
well is that simple is OK.

00:18:06.140 --> 00:18:10.630
We ended up having like
very few core mechanics.

00:18:10.630 --> 00:18:12.690
But then because of
the setting that we had

00:18:12.690 --> 00:18:16.170
and because people connected
well with our game,

00:18:16.170 --> 00:18:19.214
I think people are
still able to get--

00:18:19.214 --> 00:18:21.380
we think people were still
able to get enjoyment out

00:18:21.380 --> 00:18:25.330
of the game because of those.

00:18:25.330 --> 00:18:27.890
So now what went wrong?

00:18:27.890 --> 00:18:31.870
So first, Hex Flixel,
AKA what do you mean it's

00:18:31.870 --> 00:18:33.600
not on Stack Overflow?

00:18:33.600 --> 00:18:38.130
So Hex Flixel, while it did
play well with version control

00:18:38.130 --> 00:18:41.360
and I heard some horror stories
about Unity version control,

00:18:41.360 --> 00:18:43.790
Hex Flixel played pretty
well with version control.

00:18:43.790 --> 00:18:47.910
But if you ever
had an issue, you

00:18:47.910 --> 00:18:49.590
were pretty much out of luck.

00:18:49.590 --> 00:18:56.260
You could search on Google, and
you'd get like zero results.

00:18:56.260 --> 00:18:58.750
Sometimes the official
documentation wouldn't even

00:18:58.750 --> 00:19:00.590
turn up on a Google
search result.

00:19:00.590 --> 00:19:05.720
So documentation was
a little bit lacking.

00:19:05.720 --> 00:19:08.470
I think the second thing
that we could have improve on

00:19:08.470 --> 00:19:11.500
is that paperwork
is not management.

00:19:11.500 --> 00:19:14.220
I think in the
class in particular,

00:19:14.220 --> 00:19:16.830
this isn't emphasized
enough, is that you

00:19:16.830 --> 00:19:20.050
can do all these agile
development methods,

00:19:20.050 --> 00:19:22.610
like you can have a sprint
task list and everything.

00:19:22.610 --> 00:19:26.160
But unless if you actually
have people who are actively

00:19:26.160 --> 00:19:28.430
taking charge and
managing a project,

00:19:28.430 --> 00:19:33.860
I think stuff still
won't get done.

00:19:33.860 --> 00:19:36.470
I think that's something
that could be improved

00:19:36.470 --> 00:19:39.260
in the future in this class is
like spend less time worrying

00:19:39.260 --> 00:19:41.410
about paperwork, spend
more time actually

00:19:41.410 --> 00:19:46.490
like teaching about how to
handle personal situations.

00:19:46.490 --> 00:19:49.950
Like what happens if
someone doesn't have time.

00:19:49.950 --> 00:19:53.080
Or what happens if
somebody like does this?

00:19:53.080 --> 00:19:57.790
And so learning those managerial
skills isn't a trivial task.

00:19:57.790 --> 00:20:00.840
And I think in the
beginning, we underestimated

00:20:00.840 --> 00:20:06.960
how much those issues would
be a roadblock to progress.

00:20:06.960 --> 00:20:09.480
And then the third thing
that went wrong I guess

00:20:09.480 --> 00:20:11.480
is that responsibility
is shared.

00:20:11.480 --> 00:20:14.990
So even if somebody has
a role assigned to them,

00:20:14.990 --> 00:20:17.430
we should all still
like take the time

00:20:17.430 --> 00:20:20.490
to make sure that like everybody
is completing their role.

00:20:20.490 --> 00:20:24.460
So just making sure that people
are checking other people,

00:20:24.460 --> 00:20:27.980
to make sure tasks don't
fall between the cracks.

00:20:27.980 --> 00:20:32.240
And so overall people
do like the idea

00:20:32.240 --> 00:20:34.490
of playing as a
certain dean of MIT.

