we had all these cool
ideas from brainstorming,

00:24:58.988 --> 00:25:02.020
and a vague idea, a
personal idea, really,

00:25:02.020 --> 00:25:03.470
of what the game would be.

00:25:03.470 --> 00:25:06.210
And that made it really
difficult to communicate.

00:25:06.210 --> 00:25:08.480
So once we had that
down, everything just

00:25:08.480 --> 00:25:10.470
became way easier.

00:25:10.470 --> 00:25:12.750
We did a lot of UI testing.

00:25:12.750 --> 00:25:16.136
Even before we were sure about
the game would specifically be,

00:25:16.136 --> 00:25:18.260
we knew that was going to
involve adding components

00:25:18.260 --> 00:25:19.220
to a ship.

00:25:19.220 --> 00:25:22.680
And so we knew we could UI test
that and see how people manage

00:25:22.680 --> 00:25:25.420
with different ways of adding
those kind of components,

00:25:25.420 --> 00:25:27.680
or customizing their ship.

00:25:27.680 --> 00:25:31.300
Hex Flixel, we found it really
simple to work with actually.

00:25:31.300 --> 00:25:35.320
And whenever we needed
to add more screens

00:25:35.320 --> 00:25:37.800
or make changes the
game, we all had

00:25:37.800 --> 00:25:40.540
a pretty intuitive understanding
of how that would go.

00:25:40.540 --> 00:25:42.580
That might also be an
artifact of coming over

00:25:42.580 --> 00:25:47.110
from Phaser, which is
very similarly structured.

00:25:47.110 --> 00:25:50.860
And on our team, we got
lucky because everybody

00:25:50.860 --> 00:25:52.380
had coding experience.

00:25:52.380 --> 00:25:54.700
And it made it a lot
easier because we were all

00:25:54.700 --> 00:25:56.560
speaking the same language.

00:25:56.560 --> 00:25:58.530
And so on a time constraint
project like this,

00:25:58.530 --> 00:26:02.287
it meant that when we talked,
we were more efficient about it.

00:26:02.287 --> 00:26:04.370
That's not to say that
there is a place for people

00:26:04.370 --> 00:26:06.390
who don't have coding
experience on these teams.

00:26:06.390 --> 00:26:08.973
It's just that when we only have
two weeks to get things done,

00:26:08.973 --> 00:26:12.570
the speed was a huge help.

00:26:12.570 --> 00:26:15.350
What went wrong was
communicating our progress

00:26:15.350 --> 00:26:16.360
on the game.

00:26:16.360 --> 00:26:19.890
We had a lot of problems
where we wouldn't

00:26:19.890 --> 00:26:21.200
talk about what was that done.

00:26:21.200 --> 00:26:22.866
We didn't know what
was even in the game

00:26:22.866 --> 00:26:24.506
because somethings
weren't clear yet.

00:26:24.506 --> 00:26:26.130
Like there was one
part where we didn't

00:26:26.130 --> 00:26:27.879
know that we could
actually add components

00:26:27.879 --> 00:26:30.880
to ship because somebody had
added that in but not actually

00:26:30.880 --> 00:26:31.970
told us.

00:26:31.970 --> 00:26:35.990
And the UI wasn't there yet
to actually make it clear.

00:26:35.990 --> 00:26:38.560
We also run into problems
with heroic efforts

00:26:38.560 --> 00:26:40.440
where the night before
something was due,

00:26:40.440 --> 00:26:43.360
somebody would like to come
in and put in all this effort.

00:26:43.360 --> 00:26:46.322
And we didn't know
what they were doing,

00:26:46.322 --> 00:26:47.780
and we didn't know
what was getting

00:26:47.780 --> 00:26:51.402
done because we just weren't
communicating about that.

00:26:51.402 --> 00:26:52.860
A problem that's
related to this is

00:26:52.860 --> 00:26:55.850
that we didn't assigned
tasks well or take ownership

00:26:55.850 --> 00:27:00.510
of what we were doing, or assign
responsibility between people.

00:27:00.510 --> 00:27:03.010
And so we ran into
problems where things just

00:27:03.010 --> 00:27:05.380
wouldn't happen for a
long spurts of time.

00:27:05.380 --> 00:27:07.070
And then we'd run
into the heroic effort

00:27:07.070 --> 00:27:09.280
problem at the end where
we're all jumping in

00:27:09.280 --> 00:27:11.880
to make things happen.

00:27:11.880 --> 00:27:13.880
We also ran into problems
where sometimes people

00:27:13.880 --> 00:27:15.556
didn't push commit
for an entire day

00:27:15.556 --> 00:27:17.430
and we had no idea what
the state of the game

00:27:17.430 --> 00:27:20.400
actually wa So what
we learned from this,

00:27:20.400 --> 00:27:23.100
and what we would do
differently next time

00:27:23.100 --> 00:27:25.590
is first we'd keep
track of our progress

00:27:25.590 --> 00:27:28.140
and make sure that
it's contiguous,

00:27:28.140 --> 00:27:31.160
whether it's using Trello,
or emails, or any other sort

00:27:31.160 --> 00:27:33.410
of solution for it,
it would be really

00:27:33.410 --> 00:27:36.300
important to make sure we all
know what the state game is,

00:27:36.300 --> 00:27:39.130
and what's being worked on.

00:27:39.130 --> 00:27:41.990
We should come up with standards
for how we're going to email

00:27:41.990 --> 00:27:42.790
and meet.

00:27:42.790 --> 00:27:45.960
We talked about this, and
said it would be a good idea,

00:27:45.960 --> 00:27:47.770
but then we didn't
actually do it.

00:27:47.770 --> 00:27:50.250
So it would be good to have a
schedule of when your team is

00:27:50.250 --> 00:27:52.787
going to meet, how
they're going to email

00:27:52.787 --> 00:27:55.370
and why they're going to email,
if it's a daily update of what

00:27:55.370 --> 00:27:58.130
you're doing, or if it's
every time you push a commit.

00:27:58.130 --> 00:28:00.320
And also coming up
with standards for how

00:28:00.320 --> 00:28:01.380
you're going to Git.

00:28:01.380 --> 00:28:03.840
Are you going to use feature
branches, and all these kind

00:28:03.840 --> 00:28:07.070
of things, or are you going
to do it all on master?

00:28:07.070 --> 00:28:09.640
And are you going to push every
time you make a new commit?

00:28:09.640 --> 00:28:12.780
Or are we going to push
at a set time every day

00:28:12.780 --> 00:28:15.781
so that we can track
it all at once?

00:28:15.781 --> 00:28:17.530
If would be good to
know who's doing what.

00:28:17.530 --> 00:28:20.530
That comes in with the idea
of communication and tracking

00:28:20.530 --> 00:28:22.180
progress.

00:28:22.180 --> 00:28:24.650
What we did at first was
we had specific domains

00:28:24.650 --> 00:28:25.880
that people were working on.

00:28:25.880 --> 00:28:28.950
Jeremy was working
on the UI, Rodrigo

00:28:28.950 --> 00:28:31.460
was working on the ship model.

00:28:31.460 --> 00:28:34.826
And this made it really
easy to assign tasks

00:28:34.826 --> 00:28:36.200
and to make sure
that things were

00:28:36.200 --> 00:28:37.870
getting done in the beginning.

00:28:37.870 --> 00:28:40.232
But then in the end, when
we had some tasks that

00:28:40.232 --> 00:28:42.440
were kind of in the middle
and we didn't specifically

00:28:42.440 --> 00:28:45.470
say what was going to
happen, we ended up

00:28:45.470 --> 00:28:48.030
with this last minute scramble
of, OK, I'll take this thing.

00:28:48.030 --> 00:28:49.280
Actually I'll take this thing.

00:28:49.280 --> 00:28:50.560
Somebody else is coming in.

00:28:50.560 --> 00:28:53.390
And it made a lot more
difficult to track

00:28:53.390 --> 00:28:55.660
what was actually getting done.

00:28:55.660 --> 00:28:58.600
You can also give
tasks to people.

00:28:58.600 --> 00:29:00.765
We were kind of reluctant
to do that at first.

00:29:00.765 --> 00:29:02.640
But we got better and
it, and it was actually

00:29:02.640 --> 00:29:05.300
super helpful to just be
like, hey, you take this.

00:29:05.300 --> 00:29:08.140
And then it's completely
clear what happening.

00:29:08.140 --> 00:29:10.470
And the very last
thing to do with this

00:29:10.470 --> 00:29:13.054
is to just ask what's happening.

00:29:13.054 --> 00:29:15.257
It's good to get some
reassurance that something

00:29:15.257 --> 00:29:17.840
actually is happening if you're
not hearing anything about it.

00:29:17.840 --> 00:29:19.250
So you can just ask someone.

00:29:19.250 --> 00:29:21.680
Hey, what are you working on?

00:29:21.680 --> 00:29:26.014
Or hey, is anybody working on
making this component up here?

00:29:26.014 --> 00:29:27.180
Then you just get an answer.

00:29:27.180 --> 00:29:30.560
And you get a lot of
peace of mind from that.

00:29:30.560 --> 00:29:33.140
It's good to set up specific
times to work together.

00:29:33.140 --> 00:29:38.110
We didn't do this enough, but it
would've been great if we had.

00:29:38.110 --> 00:29:41.950
And like I said, we made a
prototype pretty early on.

00:29:41.950 --> 00:29:43.950
But I think we could have
made one even earlier.

00:29:43.950 --> 00:29:46.840
We found that it didn't limit
our creativity or our ability

00:29:46.840 --> 00:29:47.810
to talk about the game.

00:29:47.810 --> 00:29:50.790
Instead it just gave us a
platform to work off of.

00:29:50.790 --> 00:29:53.350
So we could build
a basic prototype

00:29:53.350 --> 00:29:55.510
with some idea of
a core mechanic,

00:29:55.510 --> 00:30:00.330
and then continue to brainstorm
and expand from there.

00:30:00.330 --> 00:30:04.882
And that's basically what
we learned from this game.

00:30:04.882 --> 00:30:06.590
And moving forward,
we're looking forward

00:30:06.590 --> 00:30:10.032
to implementing
this on project 4.

